import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The Deborah narrative is set in the transition between the Late Bronze Age (LBA) and Iron Age I (roughly 1200–1150 BCE), a period of massive disruption across the eastern Mediterranean. The collapse of the palace economies of Mycenae, Hatti, and Ugarit left a power vacuum in Canaan. Into that vacuum stepped both the Sea Peoples (Philistines along the coast) and highland peoples like early Israel. The Deuteronomic apostasy formula — 'did evil, sold them, cried out, raised a deliverer' — is a theological reading of a period of intense political volatility in which no single power dominated the region.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jabin king of Canaan at Hazor represents the attempted reassertion of Canaanite urban power after the LBA destructions. Hazor (modern Tell el-Qedah) was the largest city-state in Canaan during the LBA — Amenhotep II's lists describe it as a major political center. Joshua 11 records its destruction; the LBA destruction layer at Hazor (Yigael Yadin's excavations, Stratum XIII) shows massive burning consistent with this period. But Iron Age I (Stratum XII–XI) shows renewed settlement. Jabin's 'city of Hazor' in Judges may represent this post-destruction revival of Canaanite power in the north under a dynasty that retained the name 'Jabin' (possibly a throne-name like 'Pharaoh').</p>",
    "3": "<p>Iron chariots (<em>rekeb barzel</em>) represent the decisive military technology advantage of Late Bronze Age Canaanite city-states. Chariot warfare required flat, open terrain and was devastating against infantry in the plains — which is precisely where the Israelite tribes were weakest. Egyptian records from Thutmose III at Megiddo document massive chariot forces; the Amarna letters show Canaanite rulers reporting on their chariot rosters to the pharaoh. The Jezreel Valley — flat, alluvial, opened to the sea — was chariot country. Israel's strength was in the highlands, which chariots could not traverse. Jabin's nine hundred chariots would have controlled movement across the entire Jezreel plain, cutting off the tribes of Zebulun and Naphtali from each other and from the south.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Deborah's role as prophetess-judge (<em>nəḇîʾāh šōpəṭāh</em>) has ancient Near Eastern parallels in the phenomenon of female prophets, attested in the Mari letters from the 18th century BCE (where women delivered oracles to the palace) and in Assyrian records. In ANE societies, female prophetic authority was recognized within specific roles: oracle delivery, lament leadership, and cultic song. Deborah's judicial function — holding court and hearing cases — is unusual but not without parallel in periods of social disruption when normal male leadership structures had failed. Her designation as wife of Lappidoth (<em>ʾēšet lappîḏôt</em>, 'woman of torches/lightning flashes') may be an epithet for her own fiery prophetic character rather than a husband's name.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Palm of Deborah (Tomer Devorah) between Ramah and Bethel is in the central highlands of Ephraim — a landmark in the hill country, far from the northern plains where the crisis was concentrated. Sacred trees as sites of legal assembly and divine encounter are well-attested in Canaan: the oak at Shechem (Gen 35:4; Josh 24:26), the tamarisk at Beersheba (Gen 21:33), the terebinth at Mamre (Gen 13:18). Israelites and Canaanites shared a tradition of regarding prominent trees as liminal spaces between human and divine realms. Deborah's court under the palm marks the intersection of prophetic authority and natural sacred space.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Mount Tabor (Har Tavor) is a distinctive isolated mountain rising 575m above sea level from the flat Jezreel plain, visible from great distances in all directions. Its prominence made it both a landmark and a strategic observation point — the Late Bronze Age texts describe it as a boundary marker between tribal territories. The command to muster at Tabor is tactically shrewd: the forested slopes could conceal an infantry force that the chariots could not charge uphill. Kedesh in Naphtali (Tell Qedesh, modern Qedesh) is approximately 70km north of Tabor — the distance between Deborah's base area and Barak's home territory shows the geographic scope of the mobilization required.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Kishon River (<em>naḥal qîšôn</em>) drains the Jezreel Valley and the plain of Acre westward to the sea near Haifa. It is a seasonal wadi that runs as a modest stream in summer but floods dramatically in winter and early spring when rains swell the watershed. The tactical significance is that the Kishon floodplain, when waterlogged, would turn chariot operations into a nightmare: wheels sank in alluvial mud, horses stumbled on slippery riverbanks, and the massed formation advantage of chariotry dissolved in terrain they could not navigate. YHWH 'drawing Sisera to the Kishon' is thus a military strategy that exploited seasonal hydrology — the God of the rain-bringing theophany (vv4-5) weaponizes weather against the iron-chariot army.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Barak's insistence that Deborah accompany him reflects an ancient understanding of the prophet as the bearer of the divine presence. In the ancient Near East, armies campaigned with oracular figures, cultic personnel, or sacred objects that signified divine accompaniment — the Egyptians brought the Amun image, the Assyrians brought divine standards into battle. In Israel's early period, the ark served this function (1 Sam 4). Deborah as the prophetic voice of YHWH is, in Barak's understanding, the equivalent of the divine standard: without her, he has no assurance of divine presence. His condition is theologically coherent, even if its consequence is loss of personal honor.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The transfer of military glory to a woman in this narrative participates in a broader pattern of honor-reversal characteristic of Judges: YHWH consistently works through unexpected agents (left-handed Ehud, the woman at Thebez who kills Abimelech, Jael, and Gideon the hiding farmer) to demonstrate that victory belongs to YHWH, not to conventional military prowess. In the honor culture of the Iron Age Levant, being killed by a woman was deeply shameful — it is precisely this shame that Deborah prophesies over Sisera, and that the Song of Deborah celebrates. The transfer of honor was not incidental but theological: YHWH subverts the hero-culture of the age.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zebulun and Naphtali were the two tribes most directly under Jabin's oppression — their territory in the lower Galilee was the corridor through which Hazor's power was exercised. Kedesh of Naphtali (v6) was within Naphtali's tribal allotment; the muster there reflects both geographic logic and the fact that these tribes had the most immediate stake in Sisera's defeat. The figure of ten thousand men is a round number common to ancient military counts — 'thousand' (<em>ʾelep</em>) in early Israelite contexts may sometimes indicate a tribal military unit rather than a strict count of 1,000 individuals, suggesting a large but loosely organized tribal levy.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Kenites were a metalworking clan (the name <em>Qayin</em> is related to the root for 'smith/metalworker') associated with the Midianites and with Moses's father-in-law tradition. Their semi-nomadic lifestyle — moving with herds and setting up tents rather than building permanent structures — made them natural intermediaries between tribal territories. Heber's movement northward to the oak at Zaanannim (near Kedesh in Naphtali) placed his household precisely at the intersection of Israelite and Canaanite controlled territory. His peace treaty with Jabin (v17) was the kind of political accommodation semi-nomadic groups made with dominant powers to secure grazing rights and protection — a neutral status that Jael will unilaterally revoke.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The intelligence network that informs Sisera of Barak's movements reflects the ANE surveillance system of city-states: runners, scouts, and the regular movement of traders provided information to military commanders. Hazor controlled the major trade routes through Canaan — the Via Maris (coastal highway) and the road through the Jordan Valley — and would have had informants throughout the region. Sisera's rapid mobilization (v13) shows a professional military organization capable of responding to a threat within hours. The Canaanite military machine was disciplined and well-equipped; the Israelite response was a tribal levy gathering at a mountain. The disparity in military capacity makes the subsequent victory entirely supernatural.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Harosheth-hagoyim ('forested place of the peoples') has been identified by some scholars with modern Tell el-Amr near the western end of the Jezreel Valley, where the valley narrows at the foot of the Carmel range. Its name — 'of the peoples' (<em>gôyîm</em>, nations) — suggests a mixed population including Sea Peoples elements, possibly Hurrians and Indo-European groups who had served in the late Canaanite chariot corps. Sisera himself may have been of non-Semitic origin given his name; some scholars have proposed a Luwian or Hurrian etymology. The multi-ethnic character of Canaanite military leadership was common: the LBA Canaanite armies were professional forces incorporating various Near Eastern military traditions.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The holy war formula 'YHWH has given [enemy] into your hand' (<em>nātan bəyāḏ</em>) is functionally equivalent to the divine oracle that ancient Near Eastern armies sought before battle. The Assyrians consulted Ishtar; the Babylonians consulted Marduk; the Egyptians received oracles from Amun. The oracle given before battle was not merely morale-boosting but was believed to determine the battle's outcome — if the god had 'given' the enemy, the battle was already decided in the divine realm. Israel's holy war tradition, transmitted through the prophetess, served the same function but rooted in covenant theology rather than divination: YHWH's promise precedes human action.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The routing verb <em>hāmam</em> — throwing into confusion — corresponds to what ANE texts describe as the gods intervening in battle by sending panic into the enemy army. Egyptian texts regularly describe Amun putting fear into the hearts of enemies. Hittite annals describe the storm-god causing enemies to flee. In Ugaritic mythology, Baal's defeat of Mot and Yamm is described with similar combat imagery. Judges 4's account that YHWH 'routed' Sisera's army before Barak's forces engaged places the decisive act in the divine realm — a consistent feature of Israelite holy war that differentiates it from ANE battle narratives where the god assists the human hero but the human hero wins.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The pursuit of a routed army to its base at Harosheth-hagoyim was standard ancient warfare practice: a fleeing army that regrouped could fight again, so complete pursuit was tactically necessary. The phrase 'not one was left' (<em>lōʾ nišʾar ʿaḏ ʾeḥāḏ</em>) is a standard formula for total annihilation used in Egyptian and Assyrian battle accounts as well as in Israelite texts — it signals that the victory was total and that the enemy posed no future threat. The survival of Sisera alone (on foot) introduces the next scene: the great general reduced to a fugitive, dependent on the hospitality of a nomadic woman.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Sisera's flight to the tent of Jael reflects the ancient Near Eastern institution of sanctuary or refuge — the tent of a neutral party was a recognized refuge space in the honor culture of the Levant. The peace treaty between Jabin and the house of Heber (<em>šālôm bên yāḇîn melek ḥāṣôr ûbên bêt ḥeḇer haqqênî</em>) is the formal diplomatic arrangement that made the Kenite tent a safe harbor: diplomatic immunity extended to those in protected relationships. Jael's violation of this protection — offering sanctuary then killing — was a profound transgression of ANE hospitality law, which made the host responsible for the guest's safety. The text presents this violation not as censured but as the instrument of divine justice.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jael's hospitality gestures — going out to meet him, inviting him in, covering him — follow the ANE pattern of welcoming a refugee or guest. In Bedouin custom (which preserves many ancient Semitic social customs), going out to meet a traveler, offering the tent's shade, and providing covering constitute a binding hospitality obligation. The word for her rug or cover (<em>śəmîkāh</em>) is unique in the Hebrew Bible, possibly referring to a heavy woolen cover — the nomadic woman's own woven work. By wrapping him in her own covering, Jael makes herself his protector in the fullest sense — which makes her subsequent action all the more shocking within the ANE social framework.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The offer of milk rather than water — and specifically the skin of soured or curdled milk — is a nomadic delicacy, the processed dairy product of the goat herds. In the diet of the semi-nomadic Kenites, curds (<em>ḥemʾāh</em>) were a concentrated caloric food that induced drowsiness — ancient peoples were aware of the sleep-inducing properties of warm milk. The Song of Deborah (5:25) specifies that the bowl was a 'lordly bowl' — the best vessel, the most generous portion. Jael's hospitality is maximally generous, and this excess is itself the instrument: the well-fed, well-covered, warmly greeted guest falls into a deep and vulnerable sleep.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Sisera's command to Jael to stand guard at the tent door and deny his presence to any inquirer reflects the customary expectation that a host would conceal and protect a guest. The command 'say there is no man here' reverses the normal hospitality announcement — instead of announcing the guest, the host is to deny his existence. In practice, Bedouin custom required that a host protect a guest even at personal cost; Sisera is claiming this protection while hiding in a woman's tent (the women's section of the tent was a further protection since male strangers would not enter it). Sisera's calculation is reasonable within ANE custom; it fails because Jael's loyalty to Israel overrides the protocol.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The tent peg and mallet used by Jael were tools specifically associated with women in nomadic and semi-nomadic cultures: the women pitched the tents and were responsible for their maintenance. Hittite law and various ANE records show that tent-construction was gendered female labor among pastoral peoples. Jael's skill with these implements was therefore complete — she used tools she had handled hundreds of times. The specific method — driving the peg through the temples into the ground — is a blow that would have required force and precision: the mallet blow to the peg driven through the soft tissue at the temple is anatomically lethal within seconds. The Song's version (5:26-27) elaborates the scene into a rhythmic victory celebration.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Barak's arrival to find the work already done closes the narrative's structural irony: the person who insisted on the prophet's presence to secure victory discovers that the decisive act was performed not by him but by an outsider woman. In the honor culture of Iron Age Canaan, this outcome was the most embarrassing possible: the military commander arrives to find the general killed not in battle but by a nomadic woman with a tent peg. The Song of Deborah (5:24-27) transforms this into a victory celebration rather than a source of shame for Barak — the emphasis is on YHWH's surprising choice of instruments, not on Barak's failure.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theological summary ('God humbled Jabin') uses the verb <em>kānaʿ</em> — to subdue, to bring low — which is the specific term for the reversal of enemy power in Deuteronomistic theology. The Canaanite king system — city-state monarchies that had controlled the lowlands since the Middle Bronze Age — is brought low before the highland tribal confederation that YHWH had set in motion. The battle at the Kishon and Jael's tent-peg killing represent the decisive military end of Jabin's Hazor as a political force in northern Canaan, corresponding archaeologically to the transition from Stratum XIII-XII at Tel Hazor.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The gradual military-political dominance of Israel over Jabin's remnant forces ('pressing harder and harder') reflects the actual process of Iron Age I Israelite territorial expansion in Canaan, which was not a single event but a decades-long process of demographic and military pressure. The archaeological record of Iron Age I shows increasing highland settlement (the 'collar-rim store jar' culture spreading from the central highlands outward), coexisting for generations with Canaanite lowland cities before the latter's eventual collapse or absorption. The narrative's summary of Israel 'destroying Jabin' compresses what was likely a multi-generational process of Canaanite city-state decline.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The Song of Deborah is widely considered the oldest substantial piece of Hebrew literature, with most scholars dating its composition to the 12th century BCE — near-contemporary with the events it describes. Its linguistic features include archaic verb forms (the <em>qatala</em> consecutive less common in later Hebrew), rare vocabulary, elliptical syntax, and a phonological inventory suggesting pre-monarchic composition. Comparative ancient Near Eastern literature includes Egyptian victory hymns (the Kadesh Poem of Ramesses II, c. 1274 BCE), Ugaritic battle poetry (the Baal Cycle's combat descriptions), and Mesopotamian hymns celebrating divine warriors. The Song's placement beside the prose narrative of ch4 creates a doublet similar to the Exodus narrative (Exod 14 prose + Exod 15 Song of the Sea), a well-known ANE literary convention of following prose with celebratory poetry.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The opening line's interpretation depends on the meaning of <em>pāraʿ</em> and <em>pərāʿôt</em> — words whose usage is ambiguous. Three major interpretations reflect different historical reconstructions: (1) 'when leaders led' — leaders who step forward in crisis are the catalysts; (2) 'when the people volunteered' — the freewill offering of tribal levies without compulsion; (3) 'when locks were loosened' — a Nazirite war-dedication of warriors (cf. Samson's hair as a Nazirite symbol). The third reading connects the warriors to the Nazirite institution described in Num 6, where hair is the physical sign of the vow. If this reading is correct, the Deborah-Barak forces were a vowed warband, dedicated to YHWH for this specific campaign — which would explain their confidence and the Song's emphasis on voluntary participation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The address to 'kings' and 'rulers' (<em>rōzənîm</em>) as the Song's audience situates the victory hymn in international political discourse. Egyptian victory inscriptions (the Poetic Stele of Thutmose III, the Merneptah Stele) address the king's enemies as the implied audience of the divine victory. Ugaritic poetic texts similarly claim cosmic and royal audiences for divine victories. The Song of Deborah's address to kings announces that YHWH's victory over Sisera has implications for the political order of the region — it is not merely a tribal skirmish but a declaration of divine sovereignty over the kings of Canaan.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The southern theophany tradition — YHWH marching from Seir, Edom, Paran, and Sinai — reflects an ancient geographical theology that located YHWH's mountain in the southern wilderness, distinct from both Canaan and Egypt. This tradition appears in Deut 33:2, Ps 68:8-9, Hab 3:3, and here in Judges 5:4-5. Scholars call this the 'Sinai march theophany' — a literary form in which YHWH appears as a divine warrior advancing from the south with cosmic accompaniment (earthquake, storm, fire). The form is pre-Mosaic in origin and was adapted into the Exodus tradition; its appearance in this early poem confirms that YHWH's warrior identity was associated with the southern mountains long before the settlement of Canaan.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The melting/quaking mountains before YHWH's presence echo the cosmic theophany imagery of Ugaritic myth, where Baal's storm manifestation causes mountains to shake and waters to flee. The Ugaritic Baal Cycle (KTU 1.4.VII) describes Baal's voice causing the mountains to shudder. Psalm 68 (which is closely related to Judges 5:4-5) elaborates the same tradition. The specific mention of Sinai — '<em>zeh sînay</em>, this Sinai' — within the marching-theophany poem is the poem's claim that the God who shook Sinai at the covenant is the same God who now marches against Sisera. The theological point is that the Kishon victory is a Sinai-level event: the God who legislated the covenant also enforces it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The period of Shamgar and Jael described as a time when 'highways ceased' reflects the conditions of political fragmentation and insecurity typical of Iron Age I Canaan. The breakdown of the LBA palace-based road system left the inland caravan routes unprotected. Archaeological surveys of Iron Age I show a dramatic increase in hill-country sites with defense features and a decrease in lowland habitation — populations moved away from the exposed valleys into more defensible terrain. The cessation of travel on the major roads (<em>ʾoraḥôt</em>, also meaning the paths used for trade and communication) represents the collapse of the commercial-political infrastructure that had connected Canaanite cities during the LBA.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The term <em>pərāzôn</em> (village life/open-country population) refers to the non-urban, non-fortified settlement type — the <em>bên ḥōmôt</em> or open villages without walls. These are archaeologically identifiable as the small Iron Age I villages of the central highlands: typically 0.5–2 hectares, with four-room houses (the distinctive Israelite building type), collar-rim storage jars, and no monumental architecture. The cessation of this village life means the return of the population to caves and strongholds (cf. 6:2). Deborah's self-identification as 'mother in Israel' (<em>ʾēm bəyiśrāʾēl</em>) — the one who arose to restore village life — frames the deliverance in agrarian-domestic terms: she restores the conditions for settled family life.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The reference to 'new gods' (<em>ʾĕlōhîm ḥăḏāšîm</em>) chosen by Israel reflects the religious pluralism of Iron Age I Canaan, in which Israelite communities living alongside Canaanite populations adopted Baal-Hadad, Asherah, El, and Anat as additional or alternative deities. This syncretism is not merely described in the Deuteronomistic framework but is attested archaeologically: cultic figurines (particularly Asherah figurines), inscriptions mentioning 'YHWH and his Asherah' (Kuntillet Ajrud and Khirbet el-Qom, 9th–8th century BCE), and bamot (high places) found at Israelite sites all testify to the widespread incorporation of Canaanite cult practice. The military disarmament — no shield or spear among forty thousand — is the Song's theological explanation: apostasy strips a people of its defenses.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The <em>ḥōqəqîm</em> — those who volunteer, who offer themselves freely — are the tribal commanders who chose participation rather than neutrality. The Song's celebration of voluntary military service reflects the pre-monarchic structure of early Israelite society: there was no standing army, no conscription mechanism, no central authority that could compel participation. The tribal confederacy operated on a basis of mutual obligation and voluntary response to YHWH's call through prophets and judges. The contrast with the non-participating tribes (Reuben, Gilead, Dan, Asher in vv15-17) shows that this voluntary system had significant defection problems — which is precisely why voluntary participation is celebrated so emphatically.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The social strata summoned to 'tell of it' — donkey-riders (merchants and officials), those on rich carpets (wealthy settled people), road-walkers (travelers and tradespeople) — represent the full range of Israelite society from aristocrat to commoner. Donkeys were the primary transport animal in Iron Age I Canaan; iron was not yet widely available for horse-gear, and horses were expensive luxury animals for warfare (cf. Deut 17:16's prohibition on kings multiplying horses). The 'tawny donkey' (<em>ʾătōn ṣəḥōrāh</em>) with its distinctive color was a mark of status — a well-bred donkey was a significant possession. The summons is to a cross-social recitation of YHWH's acts: the victory belongs to all Israel, not only to the warriors.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The watering places (<em>mašʾabbôt</em>) were communal gathering points in the ancient Near East — wells, springs, and cisterns served as the social centers of pastoral communities, the places where flocks were watered and news exchanged. Rebekah met Eliezer at the well (Gen 24); Rachel met Jacob at the well (Gen 29); the daughters of Zelophehad were daughters of shepherds who gathered at such places. The oral recitation of 'righteous acts of YHWH' (<em>ṣiḏqôt YHWH</em>) at the watering places describes how victory narratives were preserved and transmitted before writing was widespread — the communal gathering points were the media infrastructure of oral culture.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The double <em>ʿûrî ʿûrî</em> (awake! awake!) addressed to Deborah, and the command to Barak to 'lead away your captives,' reflect the ANE genre of the victory acclaim delivered in the aftermath of battle. Egyptian reliefs (Ramesses II's Kadesh reliefs, the Medinet Habu reliefs of Ramesses III) show victory celebrations with music, dance, and public recitation of the king's victories. The command to 'awake' (also used of YHWH in Ps 44:23, 78:65) is a rousing formula that may have accompanied performative delivery of the Song — the Song was not merely composed but sung, perhaps with dramatic gestures indicating the participants named.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The 'remnant of the noble' (<em>śārîd laʾaddîrîm</em>) who marched down captures the demographic reality of Iron Age I Israel: the tribal levies who responded were not trained soldiers but farmers, herdsmen, and craftsmen who set aside their work to answer the call. ANE military records consistently distinguish between the professional chariot-and-spear elite and the general levy of foot soldiers. The Israelite forces at the Kishon were entirely from the second category — which is what makes the victory's attribution to YHWH rather than to military skill theologically appropriate. The 'remnant' language also hints at the limited response: not all Israel came; what came was a remnant of those capable.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The tribal roll call (vv14-18) is the Song's political map of early Israel. Ephraim, Benjamin, Machir (Manasseh), Zebulun, Issachar — these represent the tribal territories of the central highlands and the northern lowlands. The geography of participation corresponds to proximity: the northern tribes (Zebulun, Naphtali, Issachar) who suffered most under Jabin's oppression came; the southern and Transjordanian tribes (Reuben, Gilead, Dan, Asher) who were more distant or had alternative interests did not. The tribal list matches roughly with the tribal territories as known from the allotment narratives of Joshua 13-21, providing important confirmation of the historical reliability of the tribal boundary traditions.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The commanders of Issachar are noted as having accompanied Deborah — Issachar's territory in the eastern Jezreel Valley placed it directly under Canaanite pressure. The 'searchings of heart' attributed to Reuben (<em>ḥiqqê lēḇ</em>, profound deliberations) is satirical: they discussed, debated, and ultimately stayed home. The social criticism embedded in the Song is unusually direct — it names and shames specific tribes for their absence. This kind of public accountability through poetry was a standard function of victory songs in the ancient Near East: the Song of Deborah is simultaneously a theological celebration and a political judgment on the behavior of Israel's constituent parts during the crisis.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Reuben's absence is attributed to comfortable pastoral life — 'the piping for the flocks' (<em>šərîqôt ʿăḏārîm</em>) and the sheepfolds. Reuben's Transjordanian territory (east of the Jordan) was wealthy pastoralist land; its distance from the Jezreel battleground, combined with the economic attractions of its flocks, produced the 'great searchings of heart' that resolved into non-participation. The satire is sharpest for Reuben because Reuben was Israel's eldest tribe — the firstborn should have led. Instead, the firstborn stayed with the sheep. This tribal criticism may reflect historical tensions in the early Israelite confederacy between the prosperous eastern settlements and the harder-pressed western tribes.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Dan's association with ships (<em>ʾŏniyyôt</em>) suggests that by the time of Deborah, some of the tribe of Dan had moved to the coastal region and become involved in maritime trade or worked as hired oarsmen for Phoenician or Philistine vessels — the 'Sea Peoples' connection that the later Dan narrative (Judg 18) will complicate. Asher's coastal location (the Mediterranean coast north of Carmel) similarly oriented that tribe toward sea-trade and the economic prosperity of the Phoenician coastal towns rather than toward the inland tribal wars. The Song's rebuke implies that economic prosperity purchased through accommodation with coastal powers corrupted the tribal solidarity of the confederacy.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Zebulun and Naphtali are the Song's heroes — their territory was the most directly threatened by Jabin's power, and they responded without hesitation. Zebulun 'risked their lives to death' (<em>ḥērap napšô lāmût</em>) — a phrase that implies the full awareness of mortal risk voluntarily accepted. In the honor culture of Iron Age I tribal societies, this kind of 'contempt for one's own life' in service of the covenant community was the highest military virtue. Naphtali 'on the heights of the field' occupied the exposed tactical position — the ridge lines above the Jezreel Valley where they could be seen by the enemy. The combination of geographic exposure and voluntary self-sacrifice makes these two tribes the Song's paradigm of covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The battle at Taanach by the waters of Megiddo places the engagement at one of the most strategically contested sites in the ancient Near East — the pass between the Jezreel Valley and the coastal plain through which the Via Maris ran. Megiddo (Tell el-Mutesellim) is the site of more recorded battles than any other point in the southern Levant: Thutmose III fought there c. 1457 BCE, and the site was so battle-associated that it became the apocalyptic battlefield of Armageddon (Rev 16:16, from Har Megiddo). The detail that the Canaanite kings 'took no plunder' despite the engagement's location at such a strategic commercial crossing is pointed: they came to plunder, they left with nothing.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Stars fighting from their courses is the Song's mythopoeic expression of cosmic alignment with YHWH's purposes. In ANE cosmology, the stars were divine beings (the heavenly council) who could be deployed in earthly affairs; Assyrian astral theology explicitly identified the planets with major deities (Ishtar with Venus, Marduk with Jupiter). The claim that stars fought against Sisera is Israel's counter-claim: the heavenly beings are not the gods of Canaan but YHWH's servants, and they act on Israel's behalf. The verse may also encode actual meteorological observation — a storm front advancing from the north (theophany from Sinai moving north) would have produced the lightning and flooding that the Song celebrates.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Kishon's flooding in the battle's critical moment connects to the hydrology of the Jezreel Valley. Archaeological and geological surveys of the plain show extensive ancient river channels and flood deposits consistent with seasonal flooding. The Kishon in flood conditions would have turned the chariot-favorable alluvial plain into an obstacle course. The Canaanite iron chariot's advantage — speed, shock power, mobility — required firm, level ground; wheels sinking into alluvial mud, horses struggling in knee-deep water, heavy chassis tilting on uneven floodbanks would have transformed the nine-hundred-chariot advantage into a liability. The Song celebrates the river as an active participant in the divine victory.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The onomatopoetic galloping of horses in retreat — <em>daharôt daharôt</em>, the drumming of hoofs — is a deliberate poetic technique to recreate the soundscape of the rout. ANE poetry frequently employed sound-imitation (onomatopoeia) for battle scenes: Egyptian battle poetry imitates the sound of weapons and horses; Ugaritic texts use repetitive structures to create acoustic patterns. The galloping hoofbeats of Sisera's chariot horses, now fleeing in panic, are the sonic counterpart to the stars fighting overhead — the whole sensory world is enrolled in the victory.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The curse of Meroz — unique in biblical literature as the only named community explicitly cursed by the angel of YHWH — is a window into early Israelite social enforcement mechanisms. Before the monarchy established a judicial system with coercive power, the primary social sanction available to the confederacy was the curse: formal exclusion from the covenant community's blessings. The <em>ʾārûr</em> (covenant curse, the opposite of <em>bārûk</em>) was the ultimate social sanction, equivalent to excommunication or outlawry. Its delivery through the divine messenger gave it maximum authority — not a human judge's verdict but the divine council's. Meroz's precise location is unknown, which may be deliberate: any community that withholds from YHWH's battles occupies the place of Meroz.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Jael receives the title 'most blessed of women' (<em>minnāšîm təḇōrak</em>) — the superlative form of the covenant blessing. This places her in the highest category of covenant beneficiaries, alongside the patriarchal women who received divine blessing (Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel). That a non-Israelite woman — a Kenite tent-dweller — receives the highest blessing in the Song says something about the inclusive scope of covenant participation: faithfulness to YHWH's purposes is recognized regardless of ethnic identity. The same superlative blessing will be applied to Mary in Luke 1:42, creating a direct intertextual connection between the two women who participate in the defeat of the enemy of God's people.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The social significance of offering curds in a lordly bowl (<em>ḥemʾāh bəsēpel ʾaddîrîm</em>) is that it exceeded the minimum hospitality requirement and constituted a generous, even royal, reception. In nomadic and semi-nomadic cultures, the quality of hospitality signaled the status of both host and guest — to offer one's best indicated that the guest was being treated as an honored visitor. The detail that Jael gave better than Sisera asked (water requested, curds given) echoes the hospitality of Abraham at Mamre (Gen 18:7-8: what was offered as modest turned out to be lavish). The extravagant hospitality makes Sisera's subsequent death more shocking — and more definitive as a violation of the trust of hospitality.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The detailed enumeration in the Song of Jael's killing technique — hand to tent peg, right hand to workmen's mallet, she hammered, she struck, she pierced, she shattered — reflects the Song's interest in the domestic implements as weapons. In ANE warrior culture, the recognition of weapons was honorific: the warrior was identified with his weapons (Goliath with his spear, Achilles with his spear). Here the implements are domestic-female: tent peg and mallet, the tools of the nomadic woman's ordinary labor. The Song's slow enumeration of each domestic implement used as a weapon is a deliberate poetic choice that celebrates the inversion of normal gender categories for combat and the empowerment of an unexpected agent.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The threefold 'sank, fell, lay' at Jael's feet is formally similar to ANE victory inscriptions that pile up verbs to describe the total defeat of the enemy. Ramesses II's Kadesh reliefs and the corresponding poetry use repeated verb clusters to describe the enemies fleeing. The verb cluster here — <em>kāraʿ, nāpal, šāḵaḇ</em> (sank, fell, lay still) — is pronounced three times, creating a ritual finality: Sisera will not rise again. The detail 'between her feet he fell dead' echoes the imagery of a warrior whose head is under the feet of the victor — the standard ANE victory iconography in which the king places his foot on the neck of the defeated enemy (cf. Josh 10:24; Ps 110:1).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The scene of Sisera's mother watching at the window is an iconic ANE image attested in visual art: the 'woman at the window' motif appears on carved ivories from Nimrud (9th century BCE), Arslan Tash, and several Phoenician sites from the Iron Age. The figure typically shows a woman leaning out of a window framed by columns, watching and waiting. Whether the image represents a goddess, a priestess, or a queen-mother watching for a king's return is debated, but its association with high-status women in palace contexts is consistent. Deborah's use of this motif for Sisera's mother may be deliberately evoking a known aristocratic image to contrast with the humble tent-dwelling Jael who killed the son that the palace-woman awaits.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The court women who construct reassuring interpretations of Sisera's delay participate in the ANE culture of palace prognostication — interpreting omens, delays, and signs to provide favorable forecasts for royal and aristocratic patrons. The Akkadian texts from Nineveh and Mari describe court interpreters who reassured anxious patrons with favorable explanations. The 'wisest ladies' (<em>ḥakəmôt śārôtêhā</em>) of Sisera's mother's court are doing precisely this: applying their interpretive skill to explain the delay as a sign of even greater victory. That the mother accepts and repeats their interpretation — 'she answers her own words back to herself' — shows the recursive self-deception of those who construct comfortable fictions rather than face hard truths.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The spoil enumerated in v30 reflects the standard Bronze and Iron Age spoil list: women (<em>raḥam</em>, the crudely euphemistic 'womb'), embroidered textiles (<em>ṣeḇaʿ riqmāh</em>), and dyed goods for the warriors' necks. ANE battle accounts regularly enumerate the spoil taken — women, textiles, metals, livestock. Egyptian reliefs at Medinet Habu and Karnak show long lines of captives and spoil being led before the king. The Song's enumeration through the mouth of Sisera's mother serves as bitter irony: the spoil she predicts is the exact opposite of what is happening — her son is the one who lies dead, his army's 'spoil' being the victory of YHWH's people.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The closing benediction — enemies perish like the wicked, lovers of YHWH shine like the rising sun — is structurally parallel to the Deuteronomic blessing-and-curse conclusion (Deut 28). The solar imagery for the righteous is cross-cultural: Egyptian iconography associated the justified dead with the solar deity Ra; Mesopotamian texts use solar metaphors for victory and divine favor. The specific comparison 'like the sun going out in its strength' (<em>kəṣēʾt haššemeš bigbûrātô</em>) describes the sun at its zenith — maximum power, unobstructed, brilliant. That this solar imagery is applied not to kings or warriors but to those who love YHWH (<em>ʾōhăḇāyw</em>) democratizes the royal metaphor: covenant love, not royal birth, produces solar glorification.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The Midianite oppression (c. 1150–1100 BCE by conventional chronology) represents a new kind of threat distinct from the Canaanite city-state domination of the earlier judge period. Midian was not a settled state with fixed cities but a confederation of nomadic and semi-nomadic peoples from the eastern desert and Arabian peninsula. The oppression pattern — raiding at harvest time, destroying crops, withdrawing before a military response could be organized — was the tactic of pastoralist-raider cultures that left no permanent garrison to attack. This asymmetric warfare was far more economically devastating than periodic military confrontation, since it targeted the subsistence base of the agricultural population year after year.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The cave-dwelling described in 6:2 has been confirmed by archaeological surveys of the central highlands: Iron Age I sites in the Ephraimite and Manassite highlands show cave habitation, rock-cut cisterns as hiding places for grain, and evidence of concealed storage facilities. The three types of refuge — <em>minharôt</em> (shafts/clefts), <em>məʿārôt</em> (caves), <em>məṣāḏôt</em> (strongholds) — correspond to different terrain features. The limestone karst topography of the Samarian highlands provided abundant natural cave systems; the archaeological site of Khirbet Nisya in the Benjamin plateau shows evidence of just such a period of concealed living during Iron Age I. The cave/winepress hiding of Gideon (v11) fits this pattern exactly.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Midianite coalition — Midian, Amalek, and the 'people of the East' (<em>bənê qeḏem</em>) — represents a broad alliance of desert-fringe peoples. 'People of the East' is a general term in biblical texts for the semi-nomadic tribal groups of the Syrian desert and northern Arabia, including groups that would later be known as Arameans, Kedarites, and early Arabs. Amalek was specifically associated with the Negev and the southern desert fringes. The combination of these groups into a raiding coalition made tactical sense: they shared knowledge of desert routes, seasonal grazing patterns, and the agricultural calendars of their targets. The alliance had no political center and thus no single point of military vulnerability.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The systematic destruction of crops 'as far as Gaza' suggests that the raids penetrated the entire length of Canaan, not merely the northern or central regions. Gaza (Tell Harube/Tell el-Ajjul area) was the southernmost major city of the coastal plain — the distance from Midian's eastern approach to Gaza represents a sweep across the entire breadth of the country. The specific mention of leaving 'no livelihood' (<em>mihyāh</em>, the means of sustaining life) and no sheep, ox, or donkey describes not just crop loss but the destruction of the entire productive agricultural system: without draft animals (oxen for plowing, donkeys for transport), the following year's agricultural cycle could not begin. This was systematic economic warfare.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The camel (<em>gāmāl</em>) is central to understanding the Midianite raids' military effectiveness. The domestication of the camel as a riding and pack animal occurred in the Arabian peninsula, with the first large-scale military use appearing in the 12th–11th centuries BCE. The camel's ability to travel 150–200 km without water, carry loads of 200-300 kg, and navigate terrain impassable to horses or donkeys gave the Midianite raiders a strategic reach and mobility that no foot army could match. The 'without number' locust comparison captures the experience of communities watching a camel-mounted raiding force appear on the horizon — a force that could arrive, devastate, and disappear back into the desert before any organized military response was possible.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The social and economic depletion described — Israel 'made very low' (<em>dālal məʾōd</em>) — corresponds to what ethnographers call the 'predatory pastoral' effect on settled agricultural communities: sustained raiding reduces agricultural surplus, population, and social cohesion, ultimately forcing either adaptation (adopting the raider's economy) or dependence (paying tribute/protection money). The cry to YHWH that follows is both religious expression and political acknowledgment: Israel has exhausted all human options and must appeal to the divine. The Deuteronomistic theology sees this extremity as the intended consequence of apostasy — only at the point of total human failure does Israel return to YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The insertion of the prophetic oracle (vv7-10) before the angelic commissioning of Gideon is unique in Judges — other judge cycles move directly from cry to deliverance. The prophet sent to diagnose the situation before YHWH sends a deliverer represents the standard prophetic pattern: covenant lawsuit precedes covenant renewal. The ANE suzerain treaty format (Hittite and Assyrian texts) includes a section of historical recitation (what the suzerain has done), a list of stipulations, and the curses/blessings for violation. The prophet's speech follows this format exactly: historical recitation (Exod from Egypt, conquest of Canaan), stipulation ('do not fear the gods of the Amorites'), and the indictment ('you have not obeyed'). The structure is legal and covenantal, not merely hortatory.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The formula 'Thus says YHWH the God of Israel' (<em>kōh ʾāmar YHWH ʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the messenger formula of the royal herald in the ancient Near East. Messengers from kings prefaced their messages with 'thus says king X' — the messenger spoke as the king's proxy, with the king's authority. The prophetic use of this formula identifies the prophet as YHWH's royal messenger: they speak with full divine authority. The recitation that follows — 'I brought you up from Egypt, I delivered you, I drove out your enemies, I gave you their land' — is the benefaction list of the suzerain treaty preamble. YHWH recounts what he has done to establish the legitimacy of his covenant demands.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The enumeration of YHWH's saving acts — delivering from Egypt, from 'all who oppressed,' driving out the pre-Israelite peoples, giving the land — compresses the salvation history from Exodus through Joshua into a single prophetic accusation. In Hittite suzerain treaties, the preamble's benefaction list was read aloud at covenant renewal ceremonies to remind the vassal of the relationship's basis. The prophet's recitation here serves the same function: it re-grounds the covenant relationship before announcing the violation. The list is also implicitly a list of what is now at risk: the same Exodus power that delivered Israel from Egypt could reverse the gift of land if covenant was not maintained.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I said to you: I am YHWH your God' — the Decalogue's opening claim (Exod 20:2; Deut 5:6) is here cited as the covenant's foundational prohibition. The specific prohibition against fearing the gods of the Amorites (<em>lōʾ tîrəʾû ʾet-ʾĕlōhê hāʾĕmōrî</em>) names the specific violation: Israel has not merely worshiped other gods in addition to YHWH but has given them the reverential fear (<em>yārēʾ</em>) that is covenant loyalty's practical expression. The Amorite gods (Baal, Asherah, Molech) were the religious system of the Canaanite population among whom Israel settled — adopting their gods was a social-political accommodation that the covenant prohibited. 'You have not obeyed my voice' is the minimal summary of the entire indictment.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ophrah (<em>ʿoprāh</em>) is identified in v11 as belonging to the clan of Abiezer (<em>ʾăḇî hāʿezrî</em>), a subdivision of the tribe of Manasseh. Its location has been proposed at modern Afula, Taybe, or other sites in the western Jezreel Valley / Manassah territory, but remains unconfirmed. The oak (<em>ʾēlāh</em>, terebinth) at Ophrah was a landmark — sacred trees in Canaan functioned as boundary markers, meeting places, and sites of divine presence. The Canaanite high places (<em>bāmôt</em>) were often associated with sacred trees and standing stones; that Ophrah has a prominent tree and later a Baal altar (v25) shows the overlap between legitimate sacred space and Canaanite cult sites. The angel's choice of this particular tree as the meeting place appropriates a space with existing numinous associations.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The salutation 'YHWH is with you, mighty warrior' (<em>YHWH ʿimmāk gibbôr heḥāyil</em>) is a formulaic address that recurs in royal commissioning texts across the ancient Near East. Egyptian royal texts (particularly the Coronation texts) address the new king with epithets of valor; Assyrian and Babylonian royal titulary consistently included terms for strength and military prowess. The difference is that Gideon receives this address before any military achievement — it is a commissioning, not a recognition. The ANE parallel that most closely resembles this form is the divine call narratives of individual figures (cf. the call of Elijah, the call of Isaiah, Jer 1:5 — 'before you were born I consecrated you'): the divine identity precedes the human accomplishment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Gideon's theodicy question — 'where are all his wonderful deeds that our fathers recounted?' — reflects the oral tradition of Exodus narrative that circulated in Israel before the written texts were compiled. The fathers told (<em>sippərû-lānû</em>, recounted to us) — the Exodus story was transmitted through communal oral recitation, the primary means of historical memory in pre-literate or semi-literate societies. Gideon's knowledge of the Exodus comes through this oral chain, not through written texts. His question is the classic lament form ('we remember your acts of old, but now...') found throughout the Psalms (Ps 44:1-3, 9; 77:11-20; 89:49-51). The theodicy question does not express unbelief but rather the tension between received theology and present experience — the fundamental problem of faith under suffering.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The divine commissioning of Gideon follows the same structural pattern as Moses's call in Exodus 3-4: theophany (burning bush/angel under the oak), commission ('save Israel'), objection ('I am not capable'), divine assurance ('I will be with you'), sign requested and given. This structural repetition is deliberate: Gideon is a second Moses, a deliverer from outside the conventional power structures, called despite his own inadequacy. In the ancient world, the legitimacy of a commission was established not by the qualifications of the messenger but by the authority of the sender — 'Have I not sent you?' is the credential, not Gideon's warrior status.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gideon's self-identification as 'the least in my father's house' and 'the weakest clan in Manasseh' reflects the ANE literary convention of the 'lowly origin' motif in call narratives. Sargon of Akkad claimed to have been born of a poor woman and raised by a gardener before becoming king — the unlikely origin legitimizes the divine choice by eliminating human explanation. Moses was raised in Pharaoh's court but fled as a fugitive; David was the youngest son, a shepherd. The pattern is consistent: YHWH's deliverers are chosen not for their existing social capital but in order that the victory will be unmistakably divine. Gideon's double claim of weakness (weakest clan, youngest in household) establishes the maximum improbability of the commission.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The divine assurance '<em>kî ʾehyeh ʿimmāk</em>' (for I will be with you) is the covenantal-presence formula at the heart of YHWH's identity. The verb <em>ʾehyeh</em> (I will be) is the first-person imperfect of <em>hāyāh</em> — the same root as the divine name YHWH (Exod 3:14: '<em>ʾehyeh ʾăšer ʾehyeh</em>, I will be what I will be'). When YHWH says 'I will be with you,' he is invoking his own name-theology: the God whose name is 'I will be' promises his being-with-you. This makes the divine presence formula more than reassurance — it is a self-revelation: YHWH's fundamental being is relational presence-with.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The request for a sign (<em>ʾôt</em>) follows the Deuteronomic prophetic sign-criterion (Deut 18:22 — the true prophet's words come true) in reverse: rather than waiting for the word to prove itself, Gideon requests a demonstrative sign before proceeding. ANE divination texts (Mesopotamian <em>bārûtu</em> divination manuals) describe elaborate procedures for obtaining divine confirmation before military campaigns — inspection of liver omens, astral signs, dreams. Israelite prophetic tradition preserved sign-requests as legitimate within certain boundaries: Gideon's request is not condemned, nor is Hezekiah's request for the shadow to go backward (2 Kgs 20:8-11). The illegitimate sign-demand is the demand for a confirming sign after a prophetic word has already been given and accepted — which is precisely what the Pharisees do in Matt 16:1.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The preparation of a 'minḥāh' — an offering gift — by Gideon follows the ANE pattern of gift-presentation to a divine messenger or divine presence. The hospitality genre (prepare food, present it, the guest eats) is being enacted, but the angel's redirection of the food to the rock (v20) transforms hospitality into sacrifice. The Levitical system of grain offerings (<em>minḥāh</em>, Lev 2) has its roots precisely in this kind of improvisational sacrifice at theophany sites — the formalization of what began as spontaneous gift-giving to divine visitors. Gideon does not yet know he is entertaining a divine presence; his hospitality will become worship when the fire falls.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The meal prepared — a young goat, an ephah of flour made into unleavened cakes — corresponds to the standard hospitality meal for honored guests described in Gen 18:6-8 (Abraham's meal for the three visitors: cakes, a calf, curds, and milk). The use of unleavened bread specifically (<em>maṣṣôt</em>) may reflect the rapid preparation required by the angel's apparent intention to leave, but it also resonates with the Passover meal's unleavened bread — associating Gideon's commissioning with the Exodus event that the prophet has just recited. The full ephah (approximately 22 liters) of flour is a large quantity for one visitor — either reflecting the cultural expectation of lavish hospitality or suggesting the scale of the offering that will follow.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The angel's instruction to place the food on the rock (<em>sellaʿ</em>, a natural outcrop) and pour the broth over it transforms the hospitality offering into an altar sacrifice. In pre-Levitical practice, natural rock outcroppings served as altars — 1 Sam 14:33-35 (Saul's altar at a rock), the altar at Mizpah (Gen 31:46), and numerous archaeological examples of 'bamot' built around natural rock formations. The angel's staff (<em>mišʿenet</em>) is the traveler's staff, a sign of the journeying, transient divine messenger — but its touch produces fire, revealing that behind the traveler's form is the divine presence that consumed the burnt offerings of the tabernacle.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The fire springing from the rock to consume the offering is the theophanic fire-sign: in ANE and Israelite theology, fire from heaven (or from an unexpected source) was the signature of divine acceptance of sacrifice. Elijah's contest on Carmel (1 Kgs 18:38), the dedication of Solomon's temple (2 Chr 7:1), Manoah's offering in Judg 13:20, and David's altar on the threshing floor (1 Chr 21:26) all feature fire consuming the sacrifice as confirmation of divine acceptance. The immediate disappearance of the angel after the fire completes the revelation: the ordinary appearance (a traveler resting under a tree) was a temporary form taken by the divine presence itself — a form dissolved once its purpose (commissioning Gideon) was accomplished.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Gideon's terror at the recognition of the divine messenger echoes the ancient belief that direct encounter with the divine was potentially fatal — a belief attested across ANE religions. In Egyptian religion, seeing the full form of a major deity without preparation was lethal; in Hittite texts, improper approach to divine statues during festivals risked divine wrath; in Mesopotamian religion, direct encounter with the <em>melammu</em> (divine radiance) of a god overwhelmed mortals. Israel shared this sensibility (Exod 33:20: 'no one may see me and live') while modifying it: YHWH chose to make himself visible for specific purposes without necessarily killing the viewer. Gideon's fear is the standard ANE theophany response.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The divine word '<em>šālôm lāk</em>, peace be to you' is the covenantal greeting that restores relationship after disruption. In ANE diplomatic language, <em>šālôm</em> (wholeness/peace/well-being) was the standard greeting between parties in covenant relationship — the Amarna letters frequently open with '<em>šulmu</em> to you and to your house.' The divine greeting thus enacts a covenantal relationship: YHWH is not the executioner but the covenant partner who speaks peace to Gideon. The assurance 'you will not die' reverses the terror of v22 and commissions the encounter's purpose: survival for the mission ahead.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The altar built at the theophany site — named YHWH-Shalom — follows the patriarchal pattern of commemorating divine encounters by building altars and naming them. Abraham named the altar on Moriah 'YHWH will provide' (Gen 22:14); Jacob named the place of his night-wrestling 'Peniel' (Gen 32:30); Moses built an altar after Amalek's defeat named 'YHWH is my banner' (Exod 17:15). These divine name-compounds (<em>YHWH + noun/attribute</em>) function as theological monuments inscribed in geography — they make the character of the divine encounter available to subsequent generations who visit the site. The altar at Ophrah bearing the name YHWH-Shalom turns a Midian-ravaged, hide-in-caves landscape into a place of divine peace.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Baal altar in Gideon's father's house is archaeological religion: bāmôt (high places) with Baal altars and Asherah poles were the standard Canaanite cultic installations. At Megiddo, Hazor, and numerous Israelite sites, archaeologists have found what appear to be bāmôt — raised platforms with standing stones, ash deposits, and animal bone accumulations consistent with sacrificial use. The Asherah pole (<em>ʾăšērāh</em>) was likely a stylized wooden post or pillar representing the goddess Asherah, Baal's consort in the Ugaritic mythology. Inscriptions from Kuntillet Ajrud (8th century BCE) mention 'YHWH and his Asherah,' showing that even in Yahwistic contexts, the Asherah-cult survived. Joash's household represents this syncretistic religious culture of Iron Age I Canaan.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The construction of the YHWH altar on top of the <em>māʿôz</em> (stronghold) 'in proper order' (<em>bammāʿărāḵāh</em>) may reflect the requirement in Exod 20:25 that altars be built of uncut stones in an undressed arrangement — not the worked-stone Canaanite altars but a simpler Israelite form. The use of the destroyed Asherah as firewood for the offering is theologically pointed: the instrument of the idolatrous cult becomes the fuel for the legitimate sacrifice. This reversal — the wood of Asherah burning on YHWH's altar — symbolically subordinates the Canaanite religious system to YHWH worship. The specific use of the cult object as fuel mirrors Josiah's later reforms (2 Kgs 23:6: 'he burned the Asherah').</p>",
    "27": "<p>Gideon's nighttime action reflects the Iron Age reality of community religion as a social structure with enforcement mechanisms. The Baal altar was not merely Joash's private property but the community's cultic infrastructure — its destruction would affect the entire town's relationship with Baal, their source of agricultural fertility (Baal was the storm/rain god, essential to Canaanite agriculture). Gideon acts at night not from personal cowardice but from a realistic reading of community resistance: daytime destruction of a communal altar would have triggered immediate mob violence. The night action mirrors the Passover pattern and the later prophetic tradition of acting in darkness when overt action would be impossible.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The community's investigation upon discovering the destroyed altar (v29) reflects the judicial processes of village communities in the ancient Near East. The legal mechanism of <em>dāraš ûḇāqaš</em> (inquire and seek) is the standard formula for judicial investigation. The identification of Gideon as the perpetrator through community investigation — rather than through divine revelation or Gideon's self-declaration — shows that the community's justice system is functioning; it is simply functioning in service of the wrong god. The demand for Gideon's execution (v30) is the community applying its religious law: the offender against the community cult is subject to death. Joash's counter-argument will reframe the entire legal question.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The communal inquiry process — 'they said to one another, who has done this?' — is the standard Ancient Near Eastern village assembly process for identifying wrongdoers. The village assembly (<em>qahal</em> or <em>ʿēḏāh</em>) had judicial functions in early Israelite society before the monarchy established formal courts. The identification of Gideon is reported without an explanation of how they knew — presumably through the servants who helped him (v27) or through the circumstantial evidence of access to the family's bull. The process is normal community justice; the abnormality is the crime's nature (destroying a Baal altar) which in this community is treated as the most serious possible offense.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The demand 'bring out your son that he may die' (<em>hôṣēʾ ʾet-binkā wəyāmōt</em>) is the community's application of the death penalty for religious offense. In Canaanite communities, desecration of a cult site would have been treated as a capital offense warranting communal execution. The demand is made to Joash as the father — family/clan heads bore responsibility for their household members' conduct and were the primary point of contact for communal justice. The choice of words (<em>hôṣēʾ</em>, bring out/give up) echoes the demand of the Sodomites for Lot to 'bring out' (<em>hôṣēʾ</em>) his guests (Gen 19:5) — the same word for the same violent demand, creating an implicit comparison between the men of Gibeah (Judg 19) and the men of Sodom.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Joash's counter-argument — 'if Baal is a god let him contend for himself' — is the earliest surviving formulation of the argument that a god incapable of defending his own honor is no god. This argument will be developed into the full polemic of the prophets: Isaiah's 'idol who cannot do good, cannot do evil' (Isa 41:23-24), Elijah's taunt on Carmel ('call louder, perhaps he is asleep,' 1 Kgs 18:27), and Jeremiah's scarecrow in a cucumber field (Jer 10:5). The logic is simple: a deity that requires human defense against offense is not divine. Joash's argument emerges from practical reasoning in a moment of crisis, but it anticipates the full theological critique of idolatry that later prophets will systematize.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The name Yerubbaal (<em>yərubbaʿal</em>, 'let Baal contend') is a polemical name-monument — it commemorates Baal's failure to retaliate against Gideon, permanently encoding Baal's impotence into Gideon's identity. The practice of naming people after divine-human encounters is well-attested in the ancient Near East: names like 'Baal-has-given,' 'El-has-heard,' and 'YHWH-is-righteousness' all encode theological claims in personal names. The specific polemical name here — 'Let Baal contend' — is permanently public: every time Gideon is called by this name, the community is reminded that Baal did not contend, that Baal did nothing. The name is a living monument to divine impotence and a standing challenge: Baal may try his contention whenever he chooses.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The Midianite, Amalek, and eastern coalition crossing the Jordan into the Jezreel Valley sets the scene for the decisive confrontation. The Jezreel Valley (also called the Valley of Esdraelon) was the premier military theater of ancient Canaan — its flat, open terrain was where chariot forces had always been decisive (cf. Judg 4-5, Josh 17:16, 1 Kgs 22, 2 Kgs 23:29). The coalition's encampment here signals their intent to use their numerical superiority and camel-mobility to dominate the entire northern territory. For Gideon's tiny force, the geography is as challenging as it was in Deborah's day — YHWH will again overcome military disadvantage through divine intervention.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The Spirit clothing Gideon (<em>rûaḥ YHWH lāḇəšāh ʾet-giḏʿôn</em>) is the pneumatic empowerment for military leadership attested in other judge narratives (Othniel 3:10, Jephthah 11:29, Samson 14:6, 19; 15:14). The 'clothing' metaphor is unique here and recurs in 1 Chr 12:18 and 2 Chr 24:20 — it may reflect a tradition in which the Spirit was conceived as an enveloping presence that transformed the bearer. In ANE religion, the divine <em>melammu</em> (radiance/glory) was believed to clothe kings and heroes invested with divine authority — the Spirit's 'clothing' of Gideon is Israel's equivalent of royal divine investiture, without the monarchy's formal apparatus.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The muster of the tribes follows the ANE military assembly protocol: the local clan is mustered first (Abiezer of Manasseh), then regional tribes (Manasseh broadly, then Asher, Zebulun, Naphtali). Messengers (<em>malʾāḵîm</em>) carrying the call were the communication mechanism — there was no postal system, no written orders, only runners carrying oral messages. The willingness of distant Asher, Zebulun, and Naphtali to respond to an unknown Gideon reflects both the urgency of the Midianite crisis (these northern tribes had suffered most) and the implicit authority of the Spirit-empowered muster call. The rapid response of so many tribes confirms the Spirit's empowerment: Gideon alone, by natural social standing, commanded no one beyond his own clan.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The fleece test (<em>gizzāh</em>, H1492, the shorn wool fleece) reflects the ANE practice of seeking divine confirmation through signs before military campaigns. Mesopotamian armies consulted liver omens and astral signs; Hittite armies sought oracles from the divine assembly; Egyptian pharaohs received divine confirmation through the oracle of Amun. Gideon's fleece test is structurally similar to these practices but purified: he is not using a specialist's divination technique but asking YHWH directly for a personal confirmation through a natural phenomenon. The difference from Israelite-condemned divination is the absence of manipulation — Gideon is not extracting an answer from a reluctant deity through technique but asking YHWH to confirm what YHWH has already promised.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The choice of the threshing floor as the test site is significant: the threshing floor was an exposed, open-air space on high ground, the most vulnerable location in the agricultural landscape. It was where Gideon began in hiding (v11 — threshing in a winepress precisely because the open threshing floor was too exposed). Now, Spirit-clothed, he places his fleece openly on the threshing floor — the same space he once avoided for fear of Midian. The sign is asked in the most exposed place: Gideon is no longer hiding. The dew on the fleece (<em>ṭal</em>, H2919) — the nightly moisture of the Palestinian climate — was YHWH's regular gift to agriculture, one of the blessings promised to the covenant-keeper (Deut 33:13, 28: 'precious dew from heaven').</p>",
    "38": "<p>The wringing of a bowlful of dew from the fleece demonstrates that the phenomenon exceeded normal dew absorption. Wool's hygroscopic properties mean that a fleece would typically absorb some ambient moisture, but wringing out enough to fill a bowl (<em>sēpel</em> H5602, a bowl of moderate size) on a dry night requires a miracle of concentration — dew on one spot, none on the surrounding ground. The specificity of the test result — 'a bowlful of water' — provides a tangible, measurable confirmation, not a vague impression. YHWH's signs in Scripture are typically unmistakable: the burning bush that is not consumed, the staff that becomes a serpent, the Kishon flooding at the right moment. The sign to Gideon is in this tradition of unambiguous divine demonstration.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The reversal test — now the fleece dry and the ground wet — eliminates the remaining natural explanation. A dry fleece while the surrounding ground is covered with dew is physically impossible by natural means: wool's hygroscopic properties would cause it to absorb ambient moisture faster than bare ground. The two-stage sign design (wet fleece/dry ground, then dry fleece/wet ground) is epistemically rigorous: each sign rules out one possible natural explanation. Together they constitute what a modern scientist would call a controlled experiment with reversed conditions. Gideon's double test is not faithlessness but careful verification — the same careful verification that Thomas's tradition in John 20:25 sought, and which Jesus met with evidence rather than rebuke.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The divine compliance — 'God did so that night' — without editorial rebuke for the second test reflects the biblical tradition of YHWH's patient accommodation of human doubt. Abraham's multiple negotiations over Sodom (Gen 18:22-33), Moses's multiple objections (Exod 3-4), and Hezekiah's requested sign (2 Kgs 20:8-11) are all met with divine response rather than condemnation. The theological principle implicit in this accommodation is that faith is not the absence of need for confirmation but the willingness to trust the confirmation when it comes. Gideon, having received two unambiguous signs, will proceed immediately to battle — the double confirmation produces decisive action, not continued hesitation.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('context', 'judges', c)
    print(f'judges mkt-context: wrote {sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())} verses across ch 4-6')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
